# {{DISPLAY_NAME}} — app contract

> APP.md is the behavioral contract and the test spec. Keep the frontmatter above — it
> makes the file readable to a later edit and to anyone auditing the app. Fill every
> section; the validate stage builds and checks the app against this file.

## What it does

One paragraph: the single job this app performs. (Single responsibility — one app, one job.)

## Inputs

What the app reads: URLs, files, a schedule trigger, CLI args, settings.

## Outputs

What the app produces, in what format, and where it writes it.

## Side effects

Files written or moved, notifications sent, state stored, network calls made.

## Step plan (tiered)

| # | Step | Tier (deterministic / local / hosted) | Model (if local/hosted) |
|---|------|---------------------------------------|-------------------------|
| 1 |      | deterministic                         | —                       |
| 2 |      | local                                 | e.g. ollama/<model>     |
| 3 |      | hosted                                | e.g. anthropic/<model>  |

- Tier is pinned here at authoring time; the run-time app does not promote a step.
- A hosted step records `<provider>/<model>` with a **verified current** identifier.
- A declared input-shape fallback (e.g. PDF text → OCR) names **both** paths here, and is
  the only exception to "one tier per step".

## Success conditions (the test spec)

- Bullet the conditions that mean the app worked. These become the generated tests:
  exact-match for deterministic steps, schema/shape/sanity + golden examples for
  model-backed steps, run against recorded fixtures.

## Run-time edge cases

- **Partial failure:** (one source down — log and continue, or fail?)
- **Empty results:** (nothing new — empty file, skip, or "nothing today"?)
- **First run vs. nth run:** (initialize/baseline — how does it know?)
- **Idempotency:** (run twice — duplicate, or detect "already done"?)
- **Output collision:** (today's file exists — overwrite, append, suffix, or fail?)

